def LateMat (df, e_cutoff):
    x = df.FCounts()[(df.FCounts().date3 > e_cutoff) | (df.FCounts().date4 > e_cutoff)]
    return x

def GenPlot(df, save_plot, out_ti,  fext, start, stop):
    """
    Parameters:
        * df = dataframe of DU material class
        * TITLE = text plot title
        * out_ti = figure title
        * save _plot = save the plot 'Y' or 'N'
        * fext = output file extension (eg '.png')
        * start = earliest date in data set (round it to the nearest century)
        * stop latest date in the dataset (round it to nearest century)
    Requires: seaborn, matplotlib.pyplot and numpy
    """
    import  matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import matplotlib.patches as mpatches
    import seaborn as sns
    import numpy as np


    df['lbl'] = df.DU +'-'+ df.Cat.fillna(df.mcls)

    x2 = df

    my_range = range(1, len(x2.index)+1)

    x_ticks = []
    for i in range(start, stop, 100):
        x_ticks.append(i)

    # Plot style
    if len(x2) > 15:
        plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    else:
        pass

    if len(x2) > 20:
        plt.yticks(my_range, x2.lbl, fontsize=12)
    else:
       
        plt.tick_params(axis = 'y', rotation = 0, labelsize = 11)


    sns.set_style("white", rc= {"xtick.bottom": True, "ytick.left": True,})
    sns.set_context("paper", font_scale = 0.9)
    plt.hlines(y=my_range, xmin=x2['date3'], xmax=x2['date4'], color='black', alpha= 1)
    plt.scatter(x2['date3'], my_range, color='black', alpha= 1, label='date3', s = 11)


    # PLot lables
    plt.yticks(my_range, x2.lbl, fontsize=9)
    plt.xticks(x_ticks, fontsize = 10)
    plt.tick_params(axis = 'x', rotation = 0)
    plt.tick_params(axis = 'y', rotation = 0, labelsize = 9)
    #plt.title("Times New Roman 18", fontname = "Times New Roman", fontsize=18)
    plt.xlabel('Production Spans', fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('DU Material Class', fontsize=12)
    
    # Plot historical events as blocks
    plt.axvspan(350, 400, alpha =0.2, color= "red")
    earthquake = mpatches.Patch(color= "red", alpha=0.2, label = " Beginning of the \n Early Byzantine \n Tectonic Paroxysm")

    plt.axvspan(430, 450, alpha = 0.2, color = "green") 
    recon =  mpatches.Patch(color= "green", alpha=0.2, label = " Beginning of Episcopal Precinct \n and House of Eustolios's \n reconstruction?")

    abandon = plt.axvspan(685, 700, alpha = 0.2, color = "blue", label = " Beginning of \n Kourion's abandoment")

    nero =  plt.axvspan(54, 117, alpha = 0.2, color = "yellow", label = " The Reigns of Nero-Trajan")

    severians = plt.axvspan(145, 211, alpha = 0.2, color = "gray", label = " The Severan Dynasty")
    plt.legend(loc ="lower center", bbox_to_anchor= (0.5, -0.3), ncol = 4, handles = [nero, severians, earthquake, recon, abandon], fontsize =10)

    #save options
    if save_plot == 'Y':
         plt.tight_layout()
         plt.savefig(out_ti + fext, dpi = 1200)
    else:
        pass

def FC_DatePlt_B(df, Vlines, save_plot, out_ti,  fext, start, stop):
    """
    Plots the date spans of of the FCounts method from the DU class

    Parameters:
        * df = = DU class object
        * Vlines = add mean and TPQ lines 'Y' or 'N'
        * out_ti = figure title
        * save _plot = save the plot 'Y' or 'N'
        * fext = output file extension (eg '.png')
    Requires: seaborn, matplotlib.pyplot and numpy
    """
    import  matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import seaborn as sns
    import numpy as np


    x = df.FCounts().sort_values(by=['date3', 'date4'])

    my_range = range(1, len(x.index)+1)

    x_ticks = []
    for i in range(start, stop, 100):
        x_ticks.append(i)

    # Plot style
    sns.set_style("white", rc= {"xtick.bottom": True, "ytick.left": True,})
    sns.set_context("paper", font_scale = 0.9)

    if len(x) > 20:
        plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    else:
        pass


    plt.hlines(y=my_range, xmin=x['date3'], xmax=x['date4'], color='black', alpha= 1)
    plt.scatter(x['date3'], my_range, color='black', alpha= 1, label='date3', s = 11)

    # Plot lables
    if len(x) > 20:
        plt.yticks(my_range, x.Seq, fontsize=12)
    else:
        plt.yticks(my_range, x.mcls +"-"+ x.Seq.astype(str), fontsize=12)
        plt.tick_params(axis = 'y', rotation = 0, labelsize = 11)
        

    

    plt.xticks(x_ticks, fontsize=10)
    plt.tick_params(axis = 'x', rotation = 0)
    plt.tick_params(axis = 'y', rotation = 0, labelsize = 8)
    #plt.title("Times New Roman 18", fontname = "Times New Roman", fontsize=18)
    plt.xlabel('Production Spans', fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('Type-Form', fontsize=12)
    plt.tight_layout()

    # Additinal 

    if Vlines == 'Y':
        # Mean Median
        plt.vlines(x = df.cdu.MPDate.mean(), ymin= 0, ymax = len(x.diag), color='blue', alpha= 1, linestyles=['--'])
        #plt.text(df.cdu.MPDate.mean() + 1, len(x.diag)+1, "MD", rotation= 0, color = 'blue')

        # TPQ
        plt.vlines(x = x.date3.max(), ymin= 0, ymax = len(x.diag), color='red', alpha= 1, linestyles=['--'])
        #plt.text(x.date3.max() + 1, len(x.diag)+1, "TPQ", rotation= 0, color ='red')
    else:
        pass

    
    # Save
    if save_plot == 'Y':
         plt.savefig(out_ti + fext, dpi = 1200)
    else:
        pass

Area A Western Sector 1: Earthquake Refuse Removal¶

This section presents the DUs that we believe provide the best evidence for fourth-century A.D. earthquake refuse removal in Area As western sector. These include DUs A603, A009 and A019A020 from TrA01, TrA01-EE and TrA05. Apart from presenting these DUs and their assemblage profiles, we also examine the impact cross-cutting had on DU A603 and assess its viability for contributing to our wider analysis of Area A Western Sector DUs. These DUs assemblages are among the most diverse and rich from within the KAGC study area

DUs A009 and 603 compared¶

A review of the latest items by material class for each DU indicates relatively good inter-DU agreement between their latest glass, coins, and fine ware. However, there is no inter-DU agreement between their lamps and amphorae. In DU A009, the latest amphoras opening production date is in the early second century A.D.; in DU A603, it is the mid-fifth century A.D. DU A009s latest lamp has an opening production date in the mid-first century A.D.; in contrast, DU A603s latest lamp has its opening production date in the early fourth century A.D. Items from Marker Groups 1 and 3 (MG1 and MG3; see Chapter 3.3) constitute the most significant parts of DU A009 and DU A603s assemblages. DU A603s assemblage is among the largest, richest, and most diverse in the study area. Its assemblage has a pronounced MG1 component represented by items associated with the architectural, display, production, tools, and special purpose functional groups. In DU A009, most MG1 items belong to the architectural, display, and production functional groups. MG3 items include a range of storage/processing, transport/storage, table ware, and illumination items; transport/storage (i.e., amphorae) is the richest of these components in both DUs. However, with only 13 unique amphora types, DU A009s amphora assemblage is not as diverse or chronologically expansive as the 25 unique forms in DU A603. These DUs share nine amphorae forms which date mainly to the Hellenistic to Mid-Roman periods. After pooling the assemblages, we find that the DU A603 assemblage contains over 85% (86.2%, n= 25) of the pooled forms while DU A007 contains c. 45% (44.8%, n = 13). Apart from its typological range, DU A603s amphora assemblage has only two forms, LRA 4 and LRA 1, with opening production dates in the fourth or fifth centuries A.D. These forms are not present in DU A009. MG3 also includes a substantial quantity of animal bone (969 fragments from DU A603 and 124 fragments from DU A009), some of which preserved evidence of burning, butchering, and bone working (Volume 2, Chapter 4).

In contrast, MG2 items are not well-represented in DU A009 or DU A603. They are limited to a few personal adornments (e.g., rings), personal items (e.g., coins), and special purpose items (e.g., terracotta figurine fragments and an incense burner fragment). Like DUs A020 and A019, the low frequency of personal items and adornments is consistent with what we might expect from items incorporated into these deposits through casual loss in a domestic context. Both DUs have a residual component consisting predominantly of Hellenistic and early Roman items with production dates earlier than 24 B.C. In DU A603, the ratio of non-residual to non-residual items is c. 3:1; in DU A009, it is c. 6:1. Both values are comparable to DU A019 and DU A020s in neighboring TrA05.

While Depositional Units A009 and A603 follow the same broad trend, comparing components of their assemblage profiles, especially the amphorae, has given us some idea of how the cross-cutting in DU A603 likely conflated several dumping episodes, including the one that produced DU A009. Based on DU A009 and A603s aggregate chronological and assemblage characteristics, we can broadly interpret them as admixtures of earthquake clean-up debris and post-quake municipal refuse. The residual items suggest that material derived from Hellenistic and Early Roman deposits, most likely from the Acropolis, also contributed to the waste streams that generated DUs A603 and A009. The comparatively high quantities of marble reduction waste, animal bone (including butchered and worked fragments), and transport/storage vessels indicate that domestic and commercial waste streams also played an essential role in shaping this sector of Area As stratigraphic biography. Like DUs A019 and A020, Marker Group 2 items are not well represented in DUs A009 and A603. Carbon buildup, sharp breaks, and in-context joins from DU A009 indicate that this material did not remain in the systemic context long before redeposition. Nevertheless, at some point after c. 450 A.D., DUs A009 and A603 entirely obscured the remaining parts of FA07 that had remained above ground to this point. Based on the available stratigraphic sections and photographs, it is clear that these deposits continue further to TrA01 and TrA01-EEs south and east.

Area A Western Sector 2: Attritional Deposits¶

Apart from deposits associated with earthquake refuse cleanup, AWS also contains two DUs, DU A007 and A016 from TrA05 and TrA11 respectively, that we believe are derived from the early 20th-century archaeological excavations at the House of Eustolios and general erosion/wash from the acropolis respectively. The sediments from both DUs are loose and contain a high proportion of fist-sized rubble inclusions which are similar to the rubble that litters the slopes around the House of Eustolios from above TrA05 and TrA11. This section presents these DUs and their assemblage profiles.

Area A Western Sector 3: Other DUs and Contexts¶

This section presents three DUs that we believe are associated with post-quarry activity unrelated to earthquake cleanup (DUs A010 & A011) and quarry-related activity respectively (DU A021). Unfortunately, these DUs assemblages are often nondescript and are comprised of undatable and/or broadly dated items (e.g. small abraded shards, corroded coins) with production ranges that can span several centuries (i.e. DU A010, A011, and A021). Nevertheless, they do provide us with interesting contextual data for modeling the stratigraphic biography of Area As Western Sector.

Non-DU Affiliated COntexts¶

Area As Western Sector also contains several non-DU affiliated contexts from TrA05 and one from TrA01-EE. Except for TrA05s Context 002, Contexts 006008 are from the trenchs southeastern corner which is located c. 30 cm below the bedrock ridge, and occupied an area of c. 1.2 m2. In general, these contexts have small assemblages that are compositionally similar to TrA05s other DUs. TrA01-EEs Context 008 is also non-DU affiliated but it is presented in the TrA01-EE case study. The remainder of this brief section deals with TrA05s contexts.

Case Studie: TrA01-EE¶

TrA01-EE (Size 2 x 4m; Datum: NW at 5 cm above ground surface, DUs: A901, A902, A009A011; Features: FA06, FA07) was positioned immediately to TrA01s east in order to clarify the stratigraphy in that trench and to investigate FA07, which was uncovered in TrA01s southeastern quadrant during the 1998 field season. KAGC team members excavated TrA01-EE during the 2000 field season, and they identified 15 contexts (001015) as well as FA06, a modern drainage cut, and small segments of utility cable (Fig. 7.22).
